<section class="section" aria-labelledby="mission-title">
  <header class="section-header">
    <h2 class="section-title" id="mission-title">Mission Brief</h2>
  </header>
  
  <div class="grid-2">
    <article class="card">
      <h3>What</h3>
      <p>A 30-day, project-based C++ curriculum. One program per day. Each builds on the previous. By Day 30: a multi-file, class-based Student Management System using vectors, algorithms, I/O validation, and clean architecture.</p>
      <p>Target: VEX V5 robotics codebase contribution. The C++ used here maps directly to PROS / VEXcode: tasks, controllers, motor groups, PID loops, state machines.</p>
    </article>
    
    <article class="card">
      <h3>Why</h3>
      <p>Tutorial hell produces passive recognition. This sprint forces active retrieval: you write from memory, diff against a reference, annotate gaps. The commit log becomes the proof of work — not a certificate, not a streak, a history of decisions and corrections.</p>
    </article>
    
    <article class="card">
      <h3>Different How</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Solved/Blank pattern:</strong> Every day has a <code>solved/</code> (reference) and <code>blank/</code> (your attempt). You study solved, close it, write blank.</li>
        <li><strong>Retrieval test:</strong> The diff <em>is</em> the test. No quizzes. No multiple choice.</li>
        <li><strong>Honest log:</strong> Commits show retries, bugs, regressions. <code>day-06: Debugging Challenge — 5 bugs injected, 5 fixed, notes attached</code>.</li>
        <li><strong>PID integration (Days 28–30):</strong> Not an afterthought. Brian Douglas's intuition-first control theory. P → PI → PID on a simulated plant. Directly applicable to VEX drivetrain / lift control.</li>
      </ul>
    </article>
    
    <article class="card">
      <h3>Scope</h3>
      <p>C++17. Standard library only. No frameworks. No external deps except the PID video series. Compiler: GCC/Clang. Build: CMake (introduced Day 5). Editor: your choice.</p>
    </article>
  </div>
</section>